            "answer_text": "I can think of three Amish people that I know exist or have existed. Nearly my entire extended family is Amish, and one time I saw an old black Amish man at a family gathering. He had the full Amish getup, long silver beard, black cap, and sleek overalls. I was little back then, but I still freaked out a little. It was just so rare! Turns out he was adopted from a South American country of some sort, and was risen Amish. Many Mennonites and some Amish are connected to Belize, leading me to believe that he is from Belize, but I\u2019m not sure. Another example is of the well-known Alan Beiler from the T.V. show \u2018Amish Mafia\u2019. This show has so many false projections of the Amish, don\u2019t even get me started. But Alan has to be one of the fakest of them all. My dad personally knew Alan Beiler, and he has told me many times that the true Alan is not the same as the one on the screen, though he was raised Amish. I can\u2019t seem to find how Alan entered the Amish church, but he was most likely adopted into an Amish family. Speaking of which, my dad has said that if Alan\u2019s Amish father could see what he was doing, he\u2019d probably have a mental breakdown. The last example is present in my family\u2019s heritage. My extended family on my mother\u2019s side bears the surname,\u201dJones\u201d. If you were to open an Amish heritage book, Jones would be the last one to find on a list of surnames. This is because years ago, a young Amish girl became acquaintance with a black farmhand. No, he wasn\u2019t a slave, the Amish family in this case did not own any black slaves. So the young Amish girl became pregnant with this farmhand\u2019s baby, and she rose him amish. Afterwards, the girl married a white Amish man and since had a large family, the oldest of them being mixed. The rest of the children had a different surname, probably Yoder but the one black child in this family was left with the Jones name. This ancestor of mine stayed in the Amish church, and had many children, who had many, many more children. This has led to the Jones Family which appears other wise normal Amish family. We had a recent reunion which consisted of a few hundred people. All from Mr. Jones many years ago. ",
