            },
            "answer_text": "I've never heard of any. The Amish are generally descended from German, Swiss, or Dutch Europeans. It's very rare for outsiders to join them because of their radically different lifestyle. You're more likely to see a black conservative Mennonite (I know one personally), but there aren't very many of them. The same thing applies to many other ethnic groups such as the Chinese and Arabs. In fact, I think black Mennonites are more common than the other two ethnicities I mentioned. EDIT: As was pointed out in a comment below, where there are black conservative Mennonites, they\u2019re most likely adopted. This happens from time to time. Another reason for low black conversion rates is that conservative Mennonites and the Amish tend to avoid settling in cities, where many black people live. ",
